git clone
#makes and exact clone of existing remote repo, copies onto your local machine, everything associated with that git repo

$ git clone <remote repo url> <local directory name>
#the basic usage command of git clone

$ git clone https://github.com/bob/example.git my_amazing_project
Cloning into 'my_amazing_project'...
remote: Counting objects: 218, done.
remote: Total 218 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)
Receiving objects: 100% (218/218), 180.21 KiB | 0 bytes/s, done.
Resolving deltas: 100% (54/54), done.
Checking connectivity... done.
$ ls
my_amazing_project/
#what happened;
#new local git repo was created called "my_amazing_project"
#all contents in the remote repo were donwloaded into new local repo
#a remote was added to local repo config, pointing to url (origin)

#use git clone when working with remote repo but no local repo is created - new projects etc
#pull open source projects

#git init - creates new local repo
#git remote add origin REMOTEURL - add an existing remote repo as a remote of an existing local repo
# git clone REMOTEURL - pull down contents of remote repo into new local repo, add remote rep to local repo pointing to remote repo
